1.3  Constraints
	•	No third-party resume parsing APIs (Affinda, Sovren, RChilli, etc.)
	•	No OpenAI, Anthropic, Gemini, or any paid LLM inference API
	•	No commercial model licenses — all models must be open-source
	•	Python-based NLP pipeline using spaCy as the primary framework
	•	Inference must run on CPU in production (GPU optional for training)
	•	API must respond within 3 seconds per resume under standard load
	•	All components must be containerisable with Docker
	•	All model weights and training data must be owned and self-hosted
1.4  Why spaCy Fine-Tuned NER Approach
spaCy is the correct choice for this use case for several interconnected reasons that together make it superior to alternatives:
	•	Maturity and Production Stability: spaCy v3+ is used in production by thousands of companies. It has a stable API, comprehensive documentation, and predictable behaviour. Models trained in spaCy v3 will behave identically in development and production.
	•	CPU-First Design: Unlike transformer models which need GPU for practical inference speed, spaCy's CNN-based token classification runs at 50–200 documents per second on CPU. This is critical for cost-controlled production deployments.
	•	Incremental Trainability: spaCy supports continual learning — you can add training examples progressively without retraining from scratch each time. This is essential for an iterative accuracy improvement strategy.
	•	Custom Entity Labels: spaCy allows you to define any entity labels you need (SKILLS, DESIGNATION, COMPANY) and train the model to recognise them. This is not possible with out-of-the-box NLP models.
	•	Integrated Pipeline: spaCy handles tokenisation, sentence segmentation, POS tagging, dependency parsing, and NER in a single unified pipeline. Each component improves the others — POS tags help NER disambiguation.
	•	.spacy Binary Format: Training data is stored in a binary format that is memory-efficient, fast to load, and validates annotation integrity automatically.
1.5  System Architecture Overview
The system consists of five major layers that process every resume in strict sequence. Each layer is independently testable, independently replaceable, and independently monitorable.
