SECTION 2
SYSTEM ARCHITECTURE (HIGH LEVEL)

2.1  End-to-End Flow
Understanding the complete data flow through the system is essential before writing a single line of code. Every engineering decision downstream must be compatible with this flow.
	•	Step 1 — Upload: Client submits a file (PDF or DOCX) via HTTP POST to the FastAPI endpoint. The file passes validation (format check, size limit, malware scan). A unique job_id is assigned and the file is stored temporarily.
	•	Step 2 — Text Extraction: The extraction engine selects the appropriate extractor based on MIME type. For PDF, pdfplumber is tried first (text-based); if it returns <50 words, Tesseract OCR is triggered (scanned PDF). For DOCX, python-docx traverses paragraph elements in DOM order.
	•	Step 3 — Cleaning: Raw text is normalised — Unicode characters are converted, excessive whitespace collapsed, special characters stripped. The cleaned text is the canonical input to all subsequent steps.
	•	Step 4 — Section Segmentation: The text is split into labelled zones (CONTACT, SUMMARY, EXPERIENCE, EDUCATION, SKILLS, CERTIFICATIONS, PROJECTS). Each zone is processed independently by the extraction engine.
	•	Step 5 — Regex Pre-Extraction: Deterministic patterns extract email, phone, LinkedIn URL, GitHub URL, and date strings. These values bypass the ML model entirely and are guaranteed to be correct when the pattern matches.
	•	Step 6 — spaCy NER Inference: The fine-tuned model processes each section's text and returns a list of entity spans with labels (NAME, SKILLS, DESIGNATION, COMPANY, EDUCATION, LOCATION, CERTIFICATION). Each span includes a confidence score derived from the model's internal probability distribution.
	•	Step 7 — Post-Processing: Raw entities are normalised (dates parsed, skills mapped to taxonomy, company names cleaned), deduplicated, and validated. The experience years calculator processes employment date ranges.
	•	Step 8 — Output Assembly: All extracted fields are assembled into the canonical JSON schema. Confidence scores are attached per field. Missing fields are flagged. The response is returned to the client.
2.2  Microservice vs Monolith Decision
Recommendation: Start Monolith, Structure for Microservices
Build Phase 1 as a single deployable unit with clear module boundaries. Each module is a Python package with a defined interface. Splitting into microservices is a structural refactor, not a rewrite, when module interfaces are clean from day one. Premature microservice decomposition adds operational overhead without accuracy benefits at early stage. Split only when you have independent scaling requirements — e.g., OCR is slow and needs horizontal scaling while NER is fast and needs vertical scaling. This decision should be revisited at Phase 3.

